[SN]TITLE[SN]
Election 2015: Economy still dominates campaign

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
The economy is expected to remain key in the general election campaign, with George Osborne in Scotland promoting Conservative policies.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
SNP leader Nicola Sturgeon will question Mr Osborne's approach to the economy as she visits Kirkcaldy.
Childcare will be the focus for the Scottish Liberal Democrats, with Willie Rennie meeting candidates in Edinburgh.
Scottish Labour leader Jim Murphy will be campaigning in Glasgow for what he calls a "fairer Scotland".
While Mr Osborne is meeting Scottish business leaders, Scottish Conservative leader Ruth Davidson will be visiting Hawick.
During a visit to the children's charity Barnardo's, Ms Sturgeon will set out her "alternative to austerity".
Mr Rennie will underline his party's commitment to childcare with a visit to an Edinburgh nursery.
Mr Murphy will spend time at Social Bite, a social venture sandwich shop, where he will outline Labour's plans for a fairer society.
Voters throughout the UK go to the polls on 7 May to choose their next MP.
Polling suggests the contest will be tight and current voting intentions indicate no one party will win an overall majority in the House of Commons.
